title A third dev environment named; GrapheneOS settled, its own ladder opened
prompt Keaton, on the macOS Tahoe host, asked to adapt the NixOS plan to this machine until the Framework arrives, work on mobile emulation testing here, and settle plainly whether Pixel phones target postmarketOS, GrapheneOS, or something else. After the first question, clarified the SLC line starts with the GrapheneOS/Pixel seam specifically.
think read the two-dev-environments-and-mobile-emulation.md spec and the SLC product brief before answering anything, per docs-implementation-sync -- confirmed the OS question already has a real, settled answer in the existing tree rather than being open: postmarketOS and GrapheneOS were never competing choices for one device. postmarketOS is named only for the Fairphone-class Glowphone (phase two, after /e/OS); GrapheneOS is Pixel-exclusive (depends on Titan-class hardware memory tagging) and is the base for the separate Pixel-line SLC product (flagship Pixel 10 Pro XL, value-tier used 7a/8a). Answered this directly before touching any files.
think checked this Mac's real tooling before assuming anything about the NixOS-adaptation question: qemu 10.2.2 already installed via Homebrew, HVF acceleration confirmed present (qemu-system-aarch64 -accel help lists hvf). This closes M0/M0-riscv's own gate on this host without waiting for the Framework -- a real, checkable fact, not an assumption.
think after Keaton's clarification (start with the GrapheneOS/Pixel seam), web-searched grapheneos.org/build directly rather than assuming GrapheneOS ships an emulator image -- confirmed it does not: their sdk_phone64_x86_64 target is a development-only build requiring the full GrapheneOS/AOSP source tree, and their own docs name KVM for acceleration, which is Linux-only and unavailable on macOS's HVF. This makes a real GrapheneOS emulator build genuinely out of reach on this Mac, not merely inconvenient -- named plainly rather than glossed over.
think attempted the practical next step (installing android-commandlinetools via Homebrew, to run a stock AOSP/Android Emulator AVD as the honest stand-in for the userland surface) and hit a real, unrelated blocker: /opt/homebrew itself is owned by a different user than the current account, a leftover from some earlier sudo brew install. This needs an interactive sudo password only Keaton can supply from a real terminal -- named the exact fix command and stopped rather than attempting a workaround that would paper over a real ownership problem.
think opened a separate G-ladder (G0-G3) in the living two-dev-environments spec rather than folding GrapheneOS into the existing M-ladder, since M0-M3 specifically name the Fairphone/postmarketOS body and reusing that numbering for a different hardware line and OS would blur two genuinely distinct hardware bodies together. Named G0 as blocked-not-gated (the tooling path is known and correct, just stuck on the ownership issue), G2 as honestly out of reach on macOS at all (needs a Linux/KVM host), and G0/G1 as testing real AOSP/Android userland -- never GrapheneOS's own hardening -- per this tree's own Two Rooms register discipline, so no future reader mistakes "the emulator boots" for "GrapheneOS is proven here."
obs this turn's real finding is architectural clarity, not a build: the Pixel/GrapheneOS and Fairphone/postmarketOS questions looked like one open decision from the prompt's own phrasing, and turn out to be two already-settled, non-competing answers once the existing docs are actually read rather than assumed unresolved.
obs the Homebrew ownership blocker is exactly the kind of system-level change (sudo, outside the project entirely) that should be named and handed to Keaton rather than attempted from inside an agent session -- an interactive sudo password cannot be supplied by a script, and blindly working around an ownership problem would risk masking a real misconfiguration rather than fixing it.
file context/specs/two-dev-environments-and-mobile-emulation.md -- new section naming this macOS host as a third interim environment; new G0-G3 GrapheneOS/Pixel ladder, honestly distinguished from the existing Fairphone/postmarketOS M-ladder
file work-in-progress/TASKS.md -- new task row recording the OS-choice clarification, the qemu/HVF confirmation, and the G-ladder's real state (G0 blocked on Homebrew ownership, G2 confirmed out of reach on macOS)
file session-logs/20260715-243000_macos_interim_env_grapheneos_ladder.bron -- this log
recommend keep-going -- once Keaton runs `sudo chown -R $(whoami) /opt/homebrew` in a real terminal, the very next mechanical step is installing android-commandlinetools and standing up G0 (an HVF-accelerated AVD) on this exact Mac, unblocking G1 (the Sala broadcaster client's Android userland, already GREEN at the Rye/Rishi layer via Sala B0/B1) immediately after.
